bib.title: Sub-Coulomb proton absorption for isotopes ofzirconium and molybdenum

free_txt: BP
Kentucky polyethylene-sphere neutron
detector, for ancillary measurements surface-barrier
proton detectors.
1.7-6.7 MeV proton beams.
The cross section values are defined by number
of incoming particles, target thickness and by the
number of product particles. The foils were bombarded
with 1.7-6.7 MeV proton beams. Target thickness was
determined via elastically scattered protons with
surface barrier detectors. Neutrons were measured with
Kentucky polyethylene-sphere detectors. This
information was used to deduce cross sections.
1 mg/cm2 self-supporting foils of isotopically
enriched zirconium and molybdenum (the 92Zr foil was
actually 0.5 mg/cm2).  The targets were expected to be
less than 99% atomically pure and from 94 to 98%
isotopically pure.
Three corrections were made to the (p,n) yields.
First, neutrons from sources other than the reaction
of interest produced ~5% backgrounds at energies
above the threshold. Second, corrections of 3-7% were
made by parameterizing the cross section energy
dependence. Third, electronics dead time caused a
loss of ~1% of the pulses at the highest counting
rates.
Except near threshold and at low energies
where cross sections were small (< 1 mb), the (p,n)
cross sections were estimated to be accurate within +-
7%. This value was obtained by adding the following
uncertainties in quadrature:
less than 1% due to counting statistics.
5% target areal density.
3% detector efficiency.
~2% background subtraction.
less than 1% due to energy loss correction
less than 1% due to beam energy uncertainty
less than 1% due to beam integration.
less than 1% due to dead time correction.
Data were obtained from the Physics Auxiliary
Publication Service.  Document No: PAPS
PRVCA-20-1700-6, Table 1.
